%I A395485 #42 Jul 04 2026 15:50:09
%S A395485 1,1,2,9,119,10287
%N A395485 Number of nonisomorphic metrizable convexities on a set of n elements.
%C A395485 A convexity C on a set X is a collection of subsets of X such that {} and X are in C, C is closed under arbitrary intersection, and C is closed under directed union.
%C A395485 A convexity C is said to be metrizable if there exists a metric d on X so that for all subsets A of X, we have that A is convex iff z in A for all x,y in A and z in X with d(x,z)+d(z,y)=d(x,y) (see van de Vel). By an isomorphism f: (X,C) -> (Y,D) of convexities, it is understood a map f so that A in C <=> f(A) in D for all subsets A of X.
%C A395485 Note that every convexity C on X induced by a metric d comes from a betweenness relation B defined by B(x,z,y)<=>d(x,z)+d(z,y)=d(x,y) for all x,y,z in X. Specifically, A is in C iff z in A whenever x,y in A, z in X, and B(x,z,y).
%C A395485 The Python program in the Links enumerates a(n) by first computing metrizable betweenness relations on a set of n elements (see A395237).
%C A395485 Every metrizable convexity on a set X is an interval convexity (see A364656), with intervals given by metric segments, so a(n)<=A367422(n).
%C A395485 Using a random metric generator on 6-sets, one can see a(6)>=6778.
%D A395485 M. L. J. van de Vel, Theory of Convex Structures, North-Holland Mathematical Library, vol. 50, North-Holland, Amsterdam, 1993.
%H A395485 Tian Vlasic, <a href="/A395485/a395485.py.txt">Python program</a>
%e A395485 a(3)=2 as there are 2 distinct metrizable convexities on a three element set. If we set X={a,b,c}, then two such convexities can be e.g.,
%e A395485   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,b},{a,c},{b,c},{a,b,c}} and
%e A395485   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,b},{a,c},{a,b,c}}.
%Y A395485 Cf. A395250, A395237, A364656, A102894.
%K A395485 nonn,more,changed
%O A395485 1,3
%A A395485 _Tian Vlasic_, May 28 2026
